SIMPLE: fippenny_bit
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fippenny bit
<hw>Fip"pen*ny bit`</hw> <pr>(? ⟦or⟧ ?)</pr>. <ety>[Corruption of
<ets>five penny bit</ets>.]</ety> <def>The Spanish half real, or one
sixteenth of a dollar, -- so called in Pennsylvania and the adjacent
States.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Before the act of Congress, Feb. 21, 1857, caused the
adoption of decimal coins and the withdrawal of foreign coinage from
circulation, this coin passed currently for 6⟦frac14⟧ cents, and was
called in New England a <xex>fourpence ha'penny</xex> or
<xex>fourpence</xex>; in New York a <xex>sixpence</xex>; in
Pennsylvania, Virginia, etc., a <xex>fip</xex>; and in Louisiana, a
<xex>picayune</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fipple</ent>⟦br⟧
